  {
    "id": 1621359391868,
    "type": "text",
    "content": "\"<h1>Condition</h1>\""
  },
  {
    "id": 1636662065710,
    "type": "grid",
    "content": [
      [
        {
          "id": 1636662074274,
          "type": "text",
          "content": "\"<h2>Live Hard Coral Cover</h2><p><span style=\\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\\\">Live Hard Coral Cover. This time-series clearly illustrates the impacts of the two major bleaching events on coral cover in the region (1998 and 2016), each characterized by downward trajectories following bleaching. Promisingly, however, it also demonstrates the capacity for reefs to recover after bleaching, if there is enough time between major disturbances. The </span><a href=\\\"https://gcrmn.net/resource/status-coral-reef-western-indian-ocean-2017/\\\" rel=\\\"noopener noreferrer\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\" style=\\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\\\">2017 GCRMN Regional Report for the WIO</a><span style=\\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\\\"> included some data which was not available for this global GCRMN analysis. The regional report suggests that live coral cover in the 1980’s and 1990’s was as high 40%, and that the reefs have not fully recovered to conditions prior to the 1998 bleaching event. There has also been a clear change in coral community structure, with </span><a href=\\\"https://gcrmn.net/resource/status-coral-reef-western-indian-ocean-2017/\\\" rel=\\\"noopener noreferrer\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\" style=\\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\\\">loss of susceptible coral species and loss of diversity</a><span style=\\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\\\">, though some acclimation and/or adaptation of corals to warming may have occurred following multiple bleaching events.</span></p>\""
        }
      ],
      [
        {
          "id": 1636662077004,
          "type": "text",
          "content": "\"<h2>Algae Cover</h2><p><span style=\\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\\\">The trend in algae cover over the last 27 years is less clear than that of hard coral cover, largely due to fewer available data and inconsistencies in monitoring. Overall, algae have remained stable at ~27%, with small increases in the late 1990s and 2000s, corresponding to declines in coral cover.</span></p>\""
        }
      ]
    ]
  },
